So that's true.

118
00:06:39,830 --> 00:06:44,270
Before we get into the weeds on mediation, I'd love for you to delineate the differences

119
00:06:44,270 --> 00:06:49,190
between arbitration and mediation, because I think a lot of people get those two things

120
00:06:49,190 --> 00:06:50,190
confused.

121
00:06:50,190 --> 00:06:51,190
That's really an important point.

122
00:06:51,190 --> 00:06:53,470
I think you're right, laypeople do get those two points confused.

123
00:06:53,470 --> 00:06:57,670
And I do remember, we spoke a little bit about this in round one, and I spoke about what

124
00:06:57,670 --> 00:07:01,630
I use as a continuum, and I call it the dispute resolution continuum.

125
00:07:01,630 --> 00:07:05,630
And if you go all the way to the left-hand side of that continuum, you start off with

126
00:07:05,630 --> 00:07:06,630
negotiation.

127
00:07:06,630 --> 00:07:10,070
As I mentioned earlier, direct negotiation, you and I are either doing a deal or we have

128
00:07:10,070 --> 00:07:11,070
a dispute.

129
00:07:11,070 --> 00:07:13,350
And I'll say to you, look, Mark, we have a dispute over here.

130
00:07:13,350 --> 00:07:16,310
I don't think it behooves either of us to try to take this to court if we can resolve

131
00:07:16,310 --> 00:07:18,670
it to our satisfaction without that.

132
00:07:18,670 --> 00:07:21,830
Let's at least sit down and talk about it and explore what some of your concerns and

133
00:07:21,830 --> 00:07:25,510
needs are, share some of mine, and see if you might be able to come up with some resolution.

134
00:07:25,510 --> 00:07:26,830
So that's negotiation.

135
00:07:26,830 --> 00:07:31,030
As you move along from left to right, along that dispute resolution continuum, then come

136
00:07:31,030 --> 00:07:35,190
to if negotiation fails, we can do mediation, as I said earlier.

137
00:07:35,190 --> 00:07:39,790
Mediation rarely, to put it into very simple terms, is facilitated negotiation, where the

138
00:07:39,790 --> 00:07:46,150
mediator is a specialist and an expert on the process of negotiation and effective communication.

139
00:07:46,150 --> 00:07:51,190
And he facilitates that communication and negotiation between the parties in a way that

140
00:07:51,190 --> 00:07:55,830
it remains productive and purposeful and helps the parties to reach resolution.

141
00:07:55,830 --> 00:08:00,630
What's important to point out in mediation is the mediator has no decision-making power.

142
00:08:00,630 --> 00:08:03,870
So the mediator can't say, this is what I'm ruling or this is what I'm saying you

143
00:08:03,870 --> 00:08:04,870
have to do.

144
00:08:04,870 --> 00:08:05,870
There is none of that at all.

145
00:08:05,870 --> 00:08:07,950
The mediator has no decision-making power.

146
00:08:07,950 --> 00:08:11,950
He is a process facilitator and he helps the parties reach agreement.

147
00:08:11,950 --> 00:08:16,270
If parties do not reach agreement, or if one party doesn't want to agree, there's no agreement.

148
00:08:16,270 --> 00:08:17,270
And that's all there is to it.

149
00:08:17,270 --> 00:08:22,590
Having said that, statistics typically show that between 85% and 95% of cases settle.

150
00:08:22,590 --> 00:08:26,750
Even litigator cases usually settle on the steps of the courthouse.

151
00:08:26,750 --> 00:08:30,350
That's only about 5% of cases that actually reach trial.

152
00:08:30,350 --> 00:08:32,870
What we're trying to do is to bring that forward.

153
00:08:32,870 --> 00:08:35,630
Why spend hundreds of thousands of dollars on litigation, where we can just bring that

154
00:08:35,630 --> 00:08:39,150
whole line forward and settle it now before it gets to that stage.

155
00:08:39,350 --> 00:08:40,350
So that's what mediation is.

156
00:08:40,350 --> 00:08:44,270
A mediation is quite broadly used in court districts across the U.S.

157
00:08:44,270 --> 00:08:47,070
And I'm pleased for Canada from what I've read as well and across the world.

158
00:08:47,070 --> 00:08:51,070
It's becoming quite a popular form of resolution, particularly given COVID now, where there's

159
00:08:51,070 --> 00:08:53,310
so much backlog on the courthouse dockets.

160
00:08:53,310 --> 00:08:59,990
Many judges will recommend or even order mediation before they're actually further in the process.

161
00:08:59,990 --> 00:09:01,190
Not uncommon at all.

162
00:09:01,190 --> 00:09:02,150
So that's mediation.

163
00:09:02,150 --> 00:09:05,230
And I call that, well, that's called this facilitative mediation.

164
00:09:05,390 --> 00:09:10,590
As we move further along the continuum, we get to what's called evaluative mediation.

165
00:09:10,590 --> 00:09:15,990
It's also mediation, but it's closer to arbitration in the sense that usually the people who practice

166
00:09:15,990 --> 00:09:19,670
facilitative mediation are usually lawyers that have been in litigation for many years

167
00:09:19,670 --> 00:09:23,190
or retired judges who are always in the courtroom mindset.

168
00:09:23,190 --> 00:09:28,070
And evaluative mediation typically is the mediator will put subtle pressure on the

169
00:09:28,070 --> 00:09:31,110
parties using the law as leverage.

170
00:09:31,110 --> 00:09:32,790
And they'll say, you know, they'll meet the party separately.

171
00:09:32,870 --> 00:09:35,350
And I'll say, look, if you went to court in this, this is what I haven't done.

172
00:09:35,350 --> 00:09:38,270
Many of these cases, this is probably the outcome you would get.

173
00:09:38,270 --> 00:09:42,390
So I would urge you to settle on that basis because otherwise it may be a lot worse for

174
00:09:42,390 --> 00:09:44,430
you and they go to the other party and do something similar.

175
00:09:44,430 --> 00:09:48,710
And so they are trying to sort of subtly strong on the parties into agreement based

176
00:09:48,710 --> 00:09:51,190
on their experience of litigation.

177
00:09:51,190 --> 00:09:55,310
So it's not yet quite ordering them to do it, but it's very strong pressure that

178
00:09:55,310 --> 00:09:57,790
they are asserting upon the parties to agree.

179
00:09:57,790 --> 00:10:02,150
So that's evaluative mediation, much closer in the continuum to arbitration.

180
00:10:02,150 --> 00:10:06,430
Moving further to the rights is arbitration and arbitration is distinct from

181
00:10:06,430 --> 00:10:10,950
mediation in that mediation is a facilitative process based on negotiation

182
00:10:10,950 --> 00:10:15,230
where arbitration is an adjudicative process where the arbitrator is basically

183
00:10:15,230 --> 00:10:16,230
a judge for hire.

184
00:10:16,230 --> 00:10:19,390
Usually he's an expert on the subject matter of the case.

185
00:10:19,390 --> 00:10:23,510
For example, if it's a construction dispute, he will have had experience in

186
00:10:23,510 --> 00:10:27,190
litigating constructed cases and be quite familiar with construction law.

187
00:10:27,190 --> 00:10:29,150
He will hear the parties cases.

188
00:10:29,150 --> 00:10:30,350
Sometimes it'll be discovery.

189
00:10:30,350 --> 00:10:31,350
Sometimes it won't.

190
00:10:31,350 --> 00:10:33,790
There may be evidence presented in the way of witnesses.

191
00:10:33,790 --> 00:10:34,790
Maybe not.

192
00:10:34,790 --> 00:10:38,190
I mean, they can design how they want that to be as opposed to a court case,

193
00:10:38,190 --> 00:10:39,790
which is based on civil procedure.

194
00:10:39,790 --> 00:10:43,270
So the nice thing about arbitration is you can decide and design how extensive

195
00:10:43,270 --> 00:10:45,670
you want the formality of the arbitration to be.

196
00:10:45,670 --> 00:10:47,830
But at the end of the day, you have no choice in arbitration.

197
00:10:47,830 --> 00:10:49,630
The arbitrator is going to make the decision for you.

198
00:10:49,630 --> 00:10:52,270
It's typically binding where before you go into that arbitration,

199
00:10:52,270 --> 00:10:54,950
you sign an arbitration agreement, which binds you to anything the

200
00:10:54,950 --> 00:10:55,830
arbitrator says.

201
00:10:55,830 --> 00:10:58,630
So that's basically an adjudicated process like a court.

202
00:10:58,630 --> 00:11:00,230
But the difference is it's less formal.

203
00:11:00,230 --> 00:11:01,230
You can do it quicker.

204
00:11:01,230 --> 00:11:04,710
You can design how formal you want the process to be, how much discovery you

205
00:11:04,710 --> 00:11:07,150
want the process to involve and so on and so forth.

206
00:11:07,150 --> 00:11:09,670
And that's the arbitration component of it.

207
00:11:09,670 --> 00:11:11,830
Arbitration is very difficult to appeal.

208
00:11:11,830 --> 00:11:13,670
It's almost impossible to appeal.

209
00:11:13,670 --> 00:11:15,230
That's part of the arbitration process.

210
00:11:15,230 --> 00:11:16,910
Only two cases in which you can appeal it.

211
00:11:16,910 --> 00:11:20,350
And that is where it's clear that the arbitrator made a gross error in

212
00:11:20,350 --> 00:11:23,590
terms of law or whether there's an unconscionable decision.

213
00:11:23,590 --> 00:11:25,070
Both difficult things to prove.

214
00:11:25,070 --> 00:11:28,750
And it's almost impossible, I would say, to appeal an arbitration.

215
00:11:28,750 --> 00:11:31,670
And then finally, moving further to the right, you've got litigation.

216
00:11:31,670 --> 00:11:35,350
And of course, litigation is, we all know litigation is all too well,

217
00:11:35,350 --> 00:11:36,390
unfortunately.

218
00:11:36,390 --> 00:11:38,070
And that's, of course, the most extreme.

219
00:11:38,070 --> 00:11:39,910
So as you move from the left to the right,

220
00:11:39,910 --> 00:11:43,990
the process has become more invasive and more expensive and costly.

221
00:11:43,990 --> 00:11:46,350
As you go from negotiation and more adversarial.

222
00:11:46,350 --> 00:11:49,230
So moving from that left to right continuum, as you're moving,

223
00:11:49,230 --> 00:11:52,830
you get into more adversity and you get more expensive and costly.

224
00:11:52,830 --> 00:11:54,110
And it takes more time.

225
00:11:54,110 --> 00:11:57,190
At the end of the day, I think it's important for parties to decide,

226
00:11:57,190 --> 00:11:59,790
knowing that continuum, which makes more sense.

227
00:11:59,790 --> 00:12:02,990
Once you go straight to litigation, it's difficult to deescalate.

228
00:12:02,990 --> 00:12:06,830
If you start on the left hand side of the continuum, you can always escalate.

229
00:12:06,830 --> 00:12:09,950
So parties need to think about that very carefully and kind of remove

230
00:12:09,950 --> 00:12:13,230
the emotional side of the dispute when they're trying to make a decision.

231
00:12:13,230 --> 00:12:15,430
What process would be best to try to resolve this?

232
00:12:15,430 --> 00:12:21,350
I find it interesting that so many people don't think about that continuum

233
00:12:21,350 --> 00:12:27,030
and they default to litigation as the way that you would resolve a dispute.

234
00:12:27,030 --> 00:12:29,550
I was chatting with an organization some time ago

235
00:12:29,550 --> 00:12:34,230
and we were working on a case together and they defaulted straight to litigation.

236
00:12:34,230 --> 00:12:36,670
I was like, guys, before you go down this road,

237
00:12:36,670 --> 00:12:40,590
I really want you to consult some very good legal counsel

238
00:12:40,590 --> 00:12:47,070
because going down this road is going to lead to a significant cost to outlay.

239
00:12:47,070 --> 00:12:50,590
And it may not necessarily be worth it or worth your time

240
00:12:50,590 --> 00:12:52,750
or worth the headaches or worth the press.

241
00:12:52,750 --> 00:12:53,830
And unpredictable.

242
00:12:53,830 --> 00:12:55,750
And very unpredictable.

243
00:12:55,990 --> 00:12:59,310
You can try and forecast it as best you can, but you don't know for sure.

244
00:12:59,310 --> 00:13:05,390
Unless you have a slam dunk case, even then it may not necessarily be worth it.

245
00:13:05,390 --> 00:13:09,830
So I like your advice around starting off on the left hand side

246
00:13:09,830 --> 00:13:12,910
and then escalating from there because you may be able to resolve it

247
00:13:12,910 --> 00:13:15,510
before you get to a litigation procedure.

248
00:13:15,510 --> 00:13:17,990
And what I will say for the listeners, just so that you know,

249
00:13:17,990 --> 00:13:20,070
we're going to preface this and we're going to make sure

250
00:13:20,070 --> 00:13:21,710
that we do it in the intro.

251
00:13:21,710 --> 00:13:23,310
None of this is legal advice.

252
00:13:23,310 --> 00:13:28,990
You should still seek the counsel of a qualified attorney at all times

253
00:13:28,990 --> 00:13:33,190
with any kind of legal stuff that you're going into, obviously.

254
00:13:33,190 --> 00:13:35,950
This is meant purely for informational purposes.

255
00:13:35,950 --> 00:13:38,310
So please don't use this as legal advice.

256
00:13:38,310 --> 00:13:41,470
Please go and seek the counsel of a qualified attorney

257
00:13:41,470 --> 00:13:42,990
that can help you along the way.

258
00:13:42,990 --> 00:13:45,230
That being said, let's get into the weeds.

259
00:13:45,230 --> 00:13:48,550
When it comes to mediation, I find this to be very interesting

260
00:13:48,550 --> 00:13:51,710
and facilitated negotiation, I should say maybe more broadly

261
00:13:51,710 --> 00:13:56,350
because you get brought into situations where you may have two parties

262
00:13:56,350 --> 00:13:58,790
that don't want to go to the litigation route.

263
00:13:58,790 --> 00:13:59,910
They want to try and resolve it.

264
00:13:59,910 --> 00:14:05,310
They recognize the cost or the expense or the unpredictable nature of litigation.

265
00:14:05,310 --> 00:14:07,550
They want to try and resolve it before they get there.

266
00:14:07,550 --> 00:14:12,070
And you get brought into situations where you are maybe a neutral third party

267
00:14:12,070 --> 00:14:14,830
trying to facilitate a conversation between two other parties

268
00:14:14,830 --> 00:14:18,590
who disagree on something that want to get something done as a mediator,

269
00:14:18,590 --> 00:14:21,190
as someone who deals with this kind of stuff all the time.

270
00:14:21,190 --> 00:14:26,150
What is the process that you think about when going into those kinds of situations

271
00:14:26,150 --> 00:14:28,470
to try and make it as productive as possible?

272
00:14:28,470 --> 00:14:31,350
I try to get my mindset to a place, Mark.

273
00:14:31,350 --> 00:14:37,070
I understand that both parties, from the way they see things, make sense to them.

274
00:14:37,070 --> 00:14:39,950
It may not make sense to me, it may not make sense to you,

275
00:14:39,950 --> 00:14:43,470
but it makes sense to them based on their needs, based on their concerns,

276
00:14:43,470 --> 00:14:47,670
based on their fears, based on how the filters through which they've processed

277
00:14:47,670 --> 00:14:48,750
some of the information.

278
00:14:48,750 --> 00:14:51,830
And I say this many times, where somebody will come to speak to me,

279
00:14:51,830 --> 00:14:54,350
I'll hear the one side and I'll say, you know, it makes so much sense.

280
00:14:54,350 --> 00:14:56,710
I can't see where the other side is coming from.

281
00:14:56,710 --> 00:14:59,550
And then I'll speak to the other side and boom, there's some information

282
00:14:59,550 --> 00:15:02,830
that suddenly opens it up and things that make sense from their side too.

283
00:15:02,830 --> 00:15:04,910
And what typically happens in any kind of a dispute

284
00:15:04,910 --> 00:15:07,670
or any kind of argument or debate that we might be engaged in,

285
00:15:07,670 --> 00:15:10,270
I see things very dogmatically from my side

286
00:15:10,270 --> 00:15:12,470
and you see things very dogmatically from your side.

287
00:15:12,470 --> 00:15:15,310
I remain in my space and you remain in your space

288
00:15:15,310 --> 00:15:19,150
and there's never any exchange for me to make sure

289
00:15:19,150 --> 00:15:21,870
that I get a sense of how you're seeing it and vice versa.

290
00:15:21,870 --> 00:15:25,630
So, and I think part of that emerges from the fact that people confuse

291
00:15:25,630 --> 00:15:27,750
understanding with agreeing.

292
00:15:27,750 --> 00:15:31,630
I think people think that if I really make an effort of understanding you

293
00:15:31,630 --> 00:15:33,390
and I explain to you, I say, Mark, let me see,

294
00:15:33,390 --> 00:15:35,790
make sure that I understand you 100% here.

295
00:15:35,790 --> 00:15:39,510
And I then go on to argue your case more compellingly

296
00:15:39,510 --> 00:15:41,070
than you can argue with yourself,

297
00:15:41,070 --> 00:15:43,110
that people think, well, that means I must agree with you.

298
00:15:43,110 --> 00:15:45,190
No, it doesn't. It means that I've understood you.

299
00:15:45,310 --> 00:15:47,030
It doesn't mean that I've agreed with you.

300
00:15:47,030 --> 00:15:50,630
And people have to in their own mind be able to separate understanding with agreeing.

301
00:15:50,630 --> 00:15:53,230
So, what I try to sort of make that very much part of the media issue

302
00:15:53,230 --> 00:15:55,670
and that I facilitate understanding, I make it very clear.

303
00:15:55,670 --> 00:15:57,750
All I'm asking you to do is to try to understand,

304
00:15:57,750 --> 00:16:00,590
putting yourself in the other part issues, how they see it.

305
00:16:00,590 --> 00:16:02,070
Because if you're going to change their mind,

306
00:16:02,070 --> 00:16:03,910
you have to know where their mind is at

307
00:16:03,910 --> 00:16:05,910
and what it's like to be in their mind.

308
00:16:05,910 --> 00:16:09,070
So, the first thing is really to understand how are they seeing it.

309
00:16:09,070 --> 00:16:11,190
To the extent that you can actually bring yourself to the point,

310
00:16:11,190 --> 00:16:13,990
that makes sense. If I was them, that makes a lot of sense to me.

311
00:16:13,990 --> 00:16:15,990
I can see how they might be seeing it that way.

312
00:16:15,990 --> 00:16:18,030
So, facilitating that understanding

313
00:16:18,030 --> 00:16:20,510
and making sure that parties realize

314
00:16:20,510 --> 00:16:24,350
they can understand perfectly well without necessarily agreeing.

315
00:16:24,350 --> 00:16:27,790
I always like to refer the story of my mentor, Roger Fish in Harvard.

316
00:16:27,790 --> 00:16:29,070
I think you went to that program in Harvard.

317
00:16:29,070 --> 00:16:30,510
I did, I did, yeah.

318
00:16:30,510 --> 00:16:32,630
Probably when you and Roger had already passed away,

319
00:16:32,630 --> 00:16:34,670
Roger wrote the Getting to Yes book.

320
00:16:34,670 --> 00:16:36,910
And he was a fascinating individual in many regards

321
00:16:36,910 --> 00:16:39,870
and he was still very fortunate enough to still get his tutors.

322
00:16:39,870 --> 00:16:42,590
But he used to argue cases in front of the Supreme Court

323
00:16:42,670 --> 00:16:45,590
and the way he would argue his cases was

324
00:16:45,590 --> 00:16:48,270
he would start off by arguing his opponent's case.

325
00:16:48,270 --> 00:16:51,670
And he would argue it more eloquently and more articulately

326
00:16:51,670 --> 00:16:53,470
than his opponent argued it himself.

327
00:16:53,470 --> 00:16:55,510
And the judge would become confused

328
00:16:55,510 --> 00:16:57,710
and the judge would say, Mr. Fisher, whose side are you on?

329
00:16:57,710 --> 00:16:58,710
And Roger would say, you know,

330
00:16:58,710 --> 00:17:00,070
bear with me your honor, I'm getting there.

331
00:17:00,070 --> 00:17:03,150
And after having a demonstrated immaculate understanding

332
00:17:03,150 --> 00:17:05,150
of the other side, he would then say,

333
00:17:05,150 --> 00:17:07,070
and your honor, there is a different way

334
00:17:07,070 --> 00:17:08,150
of looking at this as well.

335
00:17:08,150 --> 00:17:09,830
And then start presenting his case,

336
00:17:09,830 --> 00:17:11,830
a very compelling debating technique.

337
00:17:11,830 --> 00:17:14,390
And I think in negotiation, that's also equally important

338
00:17:14,390 --> 00:17:17,390
where I spend much more time really trying to understand you

339
00:17:17,390 --> 00:17:27,370
and then trying to assert my own demands.

340
00:17:27,370 --> 00:17:29,570
Hey, listeners, I wanna tell you about another company

341
00:17:29,570 --> 00:17:32,850
that I run called Content Callout.

342
00:17:32,850 --> 00:17:36,970
It is a thought leadership brand marketing company.

343
00:17:36,970 --> 00:17:38,130
Now, what does that mean?

344
00:17:38,130 --> 00:17:42,450
It means that we take you as an executive or entrepreneur,

345
00:17:42,450 --> 00:17:45,370
a leader of a small or medium sized business

346
00:17:45,370 --> 00:17:48,810
and we turn you into a thought leader online.

347
00:17:48,810 --> 00:17:52,650
We take your personal brand and we amp it up to 11

348
00:17:52,650 --> 00:17:55,650
so that you can lead with confidence

349
00:17:55,650 --> 00:17:58,610
knowing that people will recognize you,

350
00:17:58,610 --> 00:18:01,610
recognize your brand and recognize your business

351
00:18:01,610 --> 00:18:04,490
because of the thought leadership approach

352
00:18:04,490 --> 00:18:06,930
that you've taken on social media

353
00:18:06,930 --> 00:18:10,410
through content creation and content distribution

354
00:18:10,410 --> 00:18:14,650
as well as engaging with all of your following online.

355
00:18:14,650 --> 00:18:16,490
How do you get involved in this?

356
00:18:16,490 --> 00:18:17,690
Easy, easy, easy.

357
00:18:17,690 --> 00:18:22,690
Just go to contentcallout.com forward slash get started

358
00:18:24,450 --> 00:18:27,010
and you will see there three different options

359
00:18:27,010 --> 00:18:30,450
that will allow you to take your thought leadership brand

360
00:18:30,450 --> 00:18:35,290
for yourself and for your business to the next level.

361
00:18:35,290 --> 00:18:37,850
We are super excited to talk to you about this.

362
00:18:37,850 --> 00:18:41,210
We've seen some massive growth with the businesses

363
00:18:41,210 --> 00:18:42,690
that we've been working with.

364
00:18:42,690 --> 00:18:45,090
Very, very exciting time for us.

365
00:18:45,090 --> 00:18:47,210
Look at that, we appreciate it.

366
00:18:47,210 --> 00:18:55,750
Now back to your show.

367
00:18:55,750 --> 00:18:57,670
Something that you said piqued my interest there

368
00:18:57,670 --> 00:18:59,270
and I think we've all been guilty of this.

369
00:18:59,270 --> 00:19:02,790
You said something to the effect of people being dogmatic

370
00:19:02,790 --> 00:19:04,310
about what they believe in.

371
00:19:04,310 --> 00:19:06,990
And sometimes I find that when people are negotiating

372
00:19:06,990 --> 00:19:09,350
there's almost like a religious adherence

373
00:19:09,350 --> 00:19:10,910
to the position that they have.

374
00:19:10,910 --> 00:19:13,990
Is there a way that you help them to,

375
00:19:13,990 --> 00:19:16,430
I don't want to say overcome that adherence

376
00:19:16,430 --> 00:19:18,270
to their position because that's important

377
00:19:18,270 --> 00:19:22,350
but maybe to try and understand more of the interests

378
00:19:22,350 --> 00:19:23,470
of the other parties,

379
00:19:23,470 --> 00:19:25,870
how do you take them through that process?

380
00:19:25,870 --> 00:19:28,470
Well, yes, what you really want to do is they come in,

381
00:19:28,470 --> 00:19:30,750
they could exchange the word dogmatic for rigid

382
00:19:30,750 --> 00:19:31,590
and I think they're both true.

383
00:19:31,590 --> 00:19:32,990
I think they're dogmatic about the position

384
00:19:32,990 --> 00:19:34,950
but they're also very rigid about the positions.

385
00:19:34,950 --> 00:19:37,630
They'd really dug in to think about a big oak tree

386
00:19:37,630 --> 00:19:40,350
with its roots firmly planted into the ground.

387
00:19:40,350 --> 00:19:42,670
That's kind of where the position is at when they come in.

388
00:19:42,670 --> 00:19:44,790
So you need to be able to loosen the earth

389
00:19:44,790 --> 00:19:48,430
around the positions and to make it much less rigid

390
00:19:48,430 --> 00:19:50,870
in terms of being able to then allow them

391
00:19:50,870 --> 00:19:52,310
to think a little bit more broadly.

392
00:19:52,910 --> 00:19:54,070
And as you know, one of the keystones

393
00:19:54,070 --> 00:19:55,550
of interest-based negotiation,

394
00:19:55,550 --> 00:19:56,950
which we're both very familiar with,

395
00:19:56,950 --> 00:19:59,310
and I feel almost inadequate in presenting this

396
00:19:59,310 --> 00:20:01,590
because it's so, I mean, any negotiation material

397
00:20:01,590 --> 00:20:03,190
you look at today speaks about interests.

398
00:20:03,190 --> 00:20:05,350
Not everybody has a depth of understanding of it

399
00:20:05,350 --> 00:20:07,790
but it's become overused and it's become,

400
00:20:07,790 --> 00:20:10,430
everybody's rebranding it in some way or another.

401
00:20:10,430 --> 00:20:11,670
And I think we spoke about it last time

402
00:20:11,670 --> 00:20:13,350
in terms of the fact there's a lot more

403
00:20:13,350 --> 00:20:16,430
in negotiation, technique and skill and processes

404
00:20:16,430 --> 00:20:17,830
and interests and positions.

405
00:20:17,830 --> 00:20:19,470
But in terms of the loosening the earth

406
00:20:19,470 --> 00:20:20,670
around those positions,

407
00:20:20,670 --> 00:20:23,550
it's important to work through the party's position

408
00:20:23,550 --> 00:20:25,270
in trying to get below the position

409
00:20:25,270 --> 00:20:27,190
because a position really is a solution.

410
00:20:27,190 --> 00:20:29,110
So for example, if I say to you,

411
00:20:29,110 --> 00:20:31,150
we want $100,000 for that.

412
00:20:31,150 --> 00:20:32,510
Well, that's one solution.

413
00:20:32,510 --> 00:20:34,030
But what are you really looking for?

414
00:20:34,030 --> 00:20:35,710
You're looking for fair compensation.

415
00:20:35,710 --> 00:20:38,310
And the other way is you can provide fair compensation

416
00:20:38,310 --> 00:20:40,110
and just $100,000, okay?

417
00:20:40,110 --> 00:20:42,190
I may be able to offer you work in the future.

418
00:20:42,190 --> 00:20:45,710
We're doing another project in place X, Y or Z.

419
00:20:45,710 --> 00:20:46,870
We do have an opening there.

420
00:20:46,870 --> 00:20:48,310
Is that something that might interest you

421
00:20:48,310 --> 00:20:50,150
as part of the compensation package?

422
00:20:50,150 --> 00:20:53,030
But as long as we stuck on $100,000, which is a position,

423
00:20:53,030 --> 00:20:54,630
that's one possible solution.

424
00:20:54,630 --> 00:20:56,110
That's not the only solution.

425
00:20:56,110 --> 00:20:58,190
And so a position, when they present a position,

426
00:20:58,190 --> 00:21:00,030
they're usually presenting the solution.

427
00:21:00,030 --> 00:21:02,030
We have to understand what the problem is

428
00:21:02,030 --> 00:21:03,670
to which they're presenting the solution.

429
00:21:03,670 --> 00:21:05,030
So in that example that I gave you,

430
00:21:05,030 --> 00:21:06,590
the solution is $100,000.

431
00:21:06,590 --> 00:21:07,590
But the problem really is

432
00:21:07,590 --> 00:21:09,430
how do we reach fair compensation?

433
00:21:09,430 --> 00:21:10,510
And I will reframe it.

434
00:21:10,510 --> 00:21:12,350
I will use the reframing technique a lot.

435
00:21:12,350 --> 00:21:13,590
And I'll say, so what you really look,

436
00:21:13,590 --> 00:21:15,350
when they come in and say $100,000,

437
00:21:15,350 --> 00:21:17,150
I'm not going to use my active listening

438
00:21:17,150 --> 00:21:18,710
to reinforce the position.

439
00:21:18,710 --> 00:21:19,870
I'll never use active listening

440
00:21:19,870 --> 00:21:22,310
to reinforce something that's not useful.

441
00:21:22,310 --> 00:21:23,390
So I will use my active listening

442
00:21:23,390 --> 00:21:25,990
to reframe that into something more useful,

443
00:21:25,990 --> 00:21:27,310
a less rigid position,

444
00:21:27,310 --> 00:21:29,070
and something that helps us define the problem.

445
00:21:29,070 --> 00:21:30,750
And I say, so what you're really looking for over here

446
00:21:30,750 --> 00:21:32,150
is fair compensation.

447
00:21:32,150 --> 00:21:32,990
Is that correct?

448
00:21:32,990 --> 00:21:33,910
I've understood you correctly.

449
00:21:33,910 --> 00:21:34,870
Yes, absolutely.

450
00:21:34,870 --> 00:21:37,150
Well, fair compensation, we just, what have we just done?

451
00:21:37,150 --> 00:21:38,510
We just loosened the earth

452
00:21:38,510 --> 00:21:41,110
around those deep roots of the big oak tree

453
00:21:41,110 --> 00:21:43,590
of what you demand, $100,000.

454
00:21:43,590 --> 00:21:45,390
And now it becomes fair compensation.

455
00:21:45,390 --> 00:21:46,630
In the process, what you've done

456
00:21:46,630 --> 00:21:50,270
is you've also created so many alternatives, right?

457
00:21:50,270 --> 00:21:52,190
To what may solve the ultimate problem,

458
00:21:52,190 --> 00:21:53,270
which is fair compensation.

459
00:21:53,270 --> 00:21:54,630
And that's where we want to go to.

460
00:21:54,630 --> 00:21:57,190
We just put in a complex negotiation right now.

461
00:21:57,190 --> 00:21:58,510
And always they try to get you,

462
00:21:58,510 --> 00:22:00,310
well, make us an offer, make us an offer.

463
00:22:00,310 --> 00:22:01,150
And you don't want to do that

464
00:22:01,150 --> 00:22:02,190
because whatever offer you make,

465
00:22:02,190 --> 00:22:03,550
you're going to be negotiating against yourself

466
00:22:03,550 --> 00:22:04,790
because they're going to flinch

467
00:22:04,790 --> 00:22:06,630
and they got to, well, you got to do better than that.

468
00:22:06,630 --> 00:22:08,630
So the technique that we use talking about options

469
00:22:08,630 --> 00:22:10,470
is we never present one offer.

470
00:22:10,470 --> 00:22:13,110
We'll present multiple equivalent simultaneous offers.

471
00:22:13,110 --> 00:22:13,990
We could do option A

472
00:22:13,990 --> 00:22:16,150
and sort of a list of components option A,

473
00:22:16,150 --> 00:22:18,750
option B, a list of components option B and option C.

474
00:22:18,750 --> 00:22:20,910
It makes it a lot more difficult for them to flinch

475
00:22:20,910 --> 00:22:22,310
because then they start looking unreasonable,

476
00:22:22,310 --> 00:22:24,230
but nothing in these offers appeal to you.

477
00:22:24,230 --> 00:22:25,310
I love that approach.

478
00:22:25,310 --> 00:22:27,470
One of the key things that I think a lot of people think

479
00:22:27,470 --> 00:22:29,030
about when it comes to mediation

480
00:22:29,030 --> 00:22:31,750
is the frustration and tension that may pop up

481
00:22:31,750 --> 00:22:34,790
in these sort of long protracted discussions.

482
00:22:34,790 --> 00:22:36,230
And I would imagine,

483
00:22:36,230 --> 00:22:37,590
and you can correct me if I'm wrong,

484
00:22:37,590 --> 00:22:41,750
that it's very rare to come to a solution in one meeting.

485
00:22:41,750 --> 00:22:44,030
I would imagine that there's several discussions

486
00:22:44,030 --> 00:22:46,030
that need to be had by both parties.

487
00:22:46,030 --> 00:22:49,550
How do you manage the tension that may exist?

488
00:22:49,550 --> 00:22:50,590
Or do you manage it?

489
00:22:50,590 --> 00:22:52,710
Is there a way for you to leverage that

490
00:22:52,710 --> 00:22:55,030
in the conversations throughout these long discussions

491
00:22:55,030 --> 00:22:56,710
that you have between both parties?

492
00:22:56,710 --> 00:22:58,950
Well, you've got to look at mediation or negotiation

493
00:22:58,950 --> 00:23:00,750
for that matter is an evolutionary process.

494
00:23:00,750 --> 00:23:02,390
And typically when they come into the mediation

495
00:23:02,390 --> 00:23:04,590
in the morning, there's a lot of tension.

496
00:23:04,590 --> 00:23:06,270
It is anger almost, you know, there's emotions

497
00:23:06,270 --> 00:23:08,310
that one side doesn't want to look at the other side

498
00:23:08,310 --> 00:23:10,990
as it progresses and as communication takes place.

499
00:23:10,990 --> 00:23:14,070
And as understanding occurs, as I mentioned earlier,

500
00:23:14,070 --> 00:23:15,750
that starts diminishing and decreasing.

501
00:23:15,790 --> 00:23:17,510
You can't do that instantly.

502
00:23:17,510 --> 00:23:19,070
That's got to evolve during the day.

503
00:23:19,070 --> 00:23:20,670
So of course, you're managing that all the time.

504
00:23:20,670 --> 00:23:21,950
And what you want to be careful of is that

505
00:23:21,950 --> 00:23:24,590
it doesn't obstruct the productive negotiation.

506
00:23:24,590 --> 00:23:26,350
Now, if there are strong emotions over there,

507
00:23:26,350 --> 00:23:27,190
you can't tell them,

508
00:23:27,190 --> 00:23:28,790
don't get so emotional or calm down.

509
00:23:28,790 --> 00:23:29,630
That doesn't work.

510
00:23:29,630 --> 00:23:31,070
So you've got to allow them to vent a little.

511
00:23:31,070 --> 00:23:32,710
I think in the history of mankind,

512
00:23:32,710 --> 00:23:35,030
telling someone to calm down has never caused them

513
00:23:35,030 --> 00:23:35,870
to calm down.

514
00:23:35,870 --> 00:23:36,710
It doesn't work.

515
00:23:36,710 --> 00:23:37,550
It doesn't work.

516
00:23:37,550 --> 00:23:38,830
Now, people still do it despite the fact

517
00:23:38,830 --> 00:23:40,430
that it's been ultimately proven

518
00:23:40,430 --> 00:23:41,510
that it never, ever works.

519
00:23:41,510 --> 00:23:42,350
Yes.

520
00:23:42,350 --> 00:23:43,470
I'm sure Adam said to Eve, calm down.

521
00:23:43,470 --> 00:23:44,910
And that was probably the beginning of his problem.

522
00:23:44,910 --> 00:23:49,910
So managing that tension and managing that frustration

523
00:23:51,390 --> 00:23:53,950
as an evolutionary process takes time.

524
00:23:53,950 --> 00:23:55,070
And do you preface?

525
00:23:55,070 --> 00:23:57,510
And time and skill and process.

526
00:23:57,510 --> 00:23:58,350
Yes.

527
00:23:58,350 --> 00:24:02,750
Do you preface the conversation with both parties to say,

528
00:24:02,750 --> 00:24:04,510
hey, as we go into this,

529
00:24:04,510 --> 00:24:06,430
there are going to be some situations

530
00:24:06,430 --> 00:24:08,510
where you may get frustrated

531
00:24:08,510 --> 00:24:10,230
or the other party may get frustrated.

532
00:24:10,230 --> 00:24:11,070
You may get tense.

533
00:24:11,070 --> 00:24:12,350
The other party may get tense.

534
00:24:12,350 --> 00:24:14,470
If and when that happens,

535
00:24:14,470 --> 00:24:16,750
do you have like rules that you said at the beginning?

536
00:24:16,750 --> 00:24:18,110
Like if you want to call a timeout,

537
00:24:18,110 --> 00:24:19,110
you call a timeout.

538
00:24:19,110 --> 00:24:20,790
How do you preface that conversation?

539
00:24:20,790 --> 00:24:21,830
So many mediators,

540
00:24:21,830 --> 00:24:23,070
and sometimes I will do that.

541
00:24:23,070 --> 00:24:24,110
It depends on the situation.

542
00:24:24,110 --> 00:24:25,710
And many mediators will start the process

543
00:24:25,710 --> 00:24:27,190
of what they call ground rules.

544
00:24:27,190 --> 00:24:28,830
You've got to be careful with those ground rules

545
00:24:28,830 --> 00:24:30,510
because the last thing you want to do

546
00:24:30,510 --> 00:24:34,430
is to come over as an authoritative school master

547
00:24:34,430 --> 00:24:35,670
telling them how to behave.

548
00:24:35,670 --> 00:24:37,630
So that becomes part of the negotiations.

549
00:24:37,630 --> 00:24:38,470
And I call that,

550
00:24:38,470 --> 00:24:39,510
and I'm sure you've heard this term,

551
00:24:39,510 --> 00:24:40,990
the talks about the talks.

552
00:24:40,990 --> 00:24:42,630
So we may have some discussion,

553
00:24:42,630 --> 00:24:45,150
maybe even in pre-mediation conversations

554
00:24:45,150 --> 00:24:46,670
we have over the phone and so on.

555
00:24:46,670 --> 00:24:48,430
And I'll always have some pre-mediation conversations

556
00:24:48,430 --> 00:24:50,030
with attorneys at a minimum.

557
00:24:50,030 --> 00:24:51,990
And we'll want to have the talks before the talks.

558
00:24:51,990 --> 00:24:53,430
Are there any things at all

559
00:24:53,430 --> 00:24:56,110
that concern you in terms of how this process might go?

560
00:24:56,110 --> 00:24:57,030
And the racings.

561
00:24:57,030 --> 00:24:59,310
Well, we're concerned about in joint sessions

562
00:24:59,310 --> 00:25:00,150
when we've tried to talk,

563
00:25:00,150 --> 00:25:01,510
just got so emotional and so angry,

564
00:25:01,510 --> 00:25:02,950
we just got so angry at each other

565
00:25:02,950 --> 00:25:04,630
and just erupted into a swearing match

566
00:25:04,630 --> 00:25:05,910
and it's been unproductive.

567
00:25:05,910 --> 00:25:08,790
I'll say, okay, how can I help you manage that

568
00:25:08,790 --> 00:25:11,030
in a way that it won't derail negotiation?

569
00:25:11,030 --> 00:25:11,870
What ideas might you have?

570
00:25:12,710 --> 00:25:14,270
So I'm getting their input.

571
00:25:14,270 --> 00:25:16,670
So they'll be negotiating the process is what we're doing.

572
00:25:16,670 --> 00:25:17,630
And again, that's something I've gotten

573
00:25:17,630 --> 00:25:19,910
from international negotiations as well.

574
00:25:19,910 --> 00:25:21,550
I mean, big international negotiations,

575
00:25:21,550 --> 00:25:24,270
a lot of work is put into the talks about the talks

576
00:25:24,270 --> 00:25:25,710
and setting that all up.

577
00:25:25,710 --> 00:25:28,310
So I've borrowed that from international negotiations

578
00:25:28,310 --> 00:25:29,870
and use that on a much smaller scale

579
00:25:29,870 --> 00:25:31,590
in terms of the mediations and negotiates

580
00:25:31,590 --> 00:25:32,430
that we do every day.

581
00:25:32,430 --> 00:25:34,310
It strikes me that the need for diplomacy

582
00:25:34,310 --> 00:25:37,230
and those types of conversations is so important

583
00:25:37,230 --> 00:25:40,790
because you can't come barreling in with your own ideas

584
00:25:40,790 --> 00:25:42,430
about how things should run.

585
00:25:42,430 --> 00:25:45,550
I love that you start the conversation with asking them

586
00:25:45,550 --> 00:25:49,990
about what they foresee as what my challenges occur.

587
00:25:49,990 --> 00:25:52,390
That in and of itself is such good advice

588
00:25:52,390 --> 00:25:53,230
for the listeners.

589
00:25:53,230 --> 00:25:54,150
I hope you caught that.

590
00:25:54,150 --> 00:25:58,070
The whole idea is prior to going into the negotiation itself,

591
00:25:58,070 --> 00:26:00,070
you would start what Raphael calls the talks

592
00:26:00,070 --> 00:26:02,510
about the talks, which is basically pre-negotiations

593
00:26:02,510 --> 00:26:06,550
to say, hey, what do you see as things that may stall this?

594
00:26:06,550 --> 00:26:08,750
Where do you think you might get frustrated?

595
00:26:08,750 --> 00:26:10,190
What do you see as challenges

596
00:26:10,190 --> 00:26:12,070
that we may need to overcome?

597
00:26:12,070 --> 00:26:13,750
Where have things gone wrong in the past?

598
00:26:13,750 --> 00:26:16,270
Those kinds of sort of broad questions

599
00:26:16,270 --> 00:26:19,270
to generate discussion around how you could help them.

600
00:26:19,270 --> 00:26:21,590
That is such a key piece of advice.

601
00:26:21,590 --> 00:26:25,910
And I think that so many people going into complex

602
00:26:25,910 --> 00:26:28,230
negotiations, and I would say that your approach

603
00:26:28,230 --> 00:26:30,350
is really good for complex negotiation,

604
00:26:30,350 --> 00:26:32,350
going into complex negotiations,

605
00:26:32,350 --> 00:26:35,590
miss that out because they're so used to the tactical

606
00:26:35,590 --> 00:26:36,790
that comes into it, right?

607
00:26:36,790 --> 00:26:40,110
They think it's about a price as per your example

608
00:26:40,430 --> 00:26:44,310
or an amount when it may be much deeper rooted than that

609
00:26:44,310 --> 00:26:47,110
and you have to get to the emotion of it

610
00:26:47,110 --> 00:26:48,590
more than anything else.

611
00:26:48,590 --> 00:26:50,910
Yeah, and it's also important for management as well

612
00:26:50,910 --> 00:26:52,990
because management are involved in negotiations

613
00:26:52,990 --> 00:26:54,070
without even realizing it.

614
00:26:54,070 --> 00:26:54,910
Yes.

615
00:26:54,910 --> 00:26:56,830
So for example, if I come to one of my employees

616
00:26:56,830 --> 00:26:58,950
and I said, please have this report done by tomorrow,

617
00:26:58,950 --> 00:27:00,350
and they said, I'm terribly sorry, sir,

618
00:27:00,350 --> 00:27:02,350
so that can't turn that around by tomorrow.

619
00:27:02,350 --> 00:27:04,710
So one way is to, through authority and command,

620
00:27:04,710 --> 00:27:06,470
well, I command you and demand that you do it

621
00:27:06,470 --> 00:27:07,910
by tomorrow, otherwise you fire.

622
00:27:07,910 --> 00:27:09,350
And that's not gonna get me very far.

623
00:27:09,350 --> 00:27:10,830
But if I say to them, I say, you're not getting

624
00:27:10,830 --> 00:27:12,350
to those infos loosening the earth

625
00:27:12,350 --> 00:27:14,590
around those roots, that rigid position.

626
00:27:14,590 --> 00:27:16,550
And I say, can you explain to me some of the constraints

627
00:27:16,550 --> 00:27:18,150
you might have, because if I understand that,

628
00:27:18,150 --> 00:27:19,990
we may be able to find some solution to that.

629
00:27:19,990 --> 00:27:22,950
And then they'll say, well, I've got to do this form,

630
00:27:22,950 --> 00:27:24,790
this person, I've got to do that for that person.

631
00:27:24,790 --> 00:27:25,750
And I'll say, do you have any ideas

632
00:27:25,750 --> 00:27:27,270
of how I might shift that around?

633
00:27:27,270 --> 00:27:28,110
What are the priorities?

634
00:27:28,110 --> 00:27:29,350
So you're asking them for the solution.

635
00:27:29,350 --> 00:27:31,870
I'm using similar techniques and management.

636
00:27:31,870 --> 00:27:33,150
You know, there's all sorts of theory

637
00:27:33,150 --> 00:27:34,550
about good management and so on,

638
00:27:34,550 --> 00:27:36,150
but managers, what they don't realize really

639
00:27:36,150 --> 00:27:37,550
is that there's so much involved

640
00:27:37,550 --> 00:27:39,870
that relates to negotiation and mediation.

641
00:27:39,870 --> 00:27:40,710
Big time.

642
00:27:40,710 --> 00:27:44,950
I can imagine that at some point in the mediation process,

643
00:27:44,950 --> 00:27:48,350
you've got to start closing towards a final solution.

644
00:27:48,350 --> 00:27:51,110
But sometimes corralling both parties

645
00:27:51,110 --> 00:27:55,190
to keep their agreements is probably quite challenging.

646
00:27:55,190 --> 00:27:58,150
Is there a way that you can get people to commit

647
00:27:58,150 --> 00:27:59,590
and keep to their commitments

648
00:27:59,590 --> 00:28:01,390
on what has been agreed to throughout

649
00:28:01,390 --> 00:28:02,990
so that you can get to a close?

650
00:28:02,990 --> 00:28:04,510
How do you manage that?

651
00:28:04,510 --> 00:28:06,190
So that gets to your earlier question, Mark,

652
00:28:06,190 --> 00:28:07,670
which I think I don't fully address,

653
00:28:07,670 --> 00:28:10,550
and that is you ask about getting the mediation resolved

654
00:28:10,550 --> 00:28:12,190
in the meeting or not.

655
00:28:12,190 --> 00:28:14,030
So, you know, some mediations will get resolved

656
00:28:14,030 --> 00:28:15,630
in a meeting, and what we will typically do

657
00:28:15,630 --> 00:28:18,230
is make sure that we write some kind of agreement

658
00:28:18,230 --> 00:28:19,910
and get that agreement signed in the meeting,

659
00:28:19,910 --> 00:28:21,350
even if it's on the back of a napkin.

660
00:28:21,350 --> 00:28:22,590
But we will get something signed

661
00:28:22,590 --> 00:28:23,910
if agreement is reached.

662
00:28:23,910 --> 00:28:25,390
But many times what happens is,

663
00:28:25,390 --> 00:28:26,310
at the end of the mediation,

664
00:28:26,310 --> 00:28:29,030
I realize there is room here for agreement.

665
00:28:29,030 --> 00:28:31,310
We haven't gotten to complete agreement just yet,

666
00:28:31,310 --> 00:28:32,390
but there is room for agreement.

667
00:28:32,390 --> 00:28:33,910
There's definitely room to move over here,

668
00:28:33,910 --> 00:28:35,150
and I think I can do something.

669
00:28:35,230 --> 00:28:37,630
I will continue working with the parties offline

670
00:28:37,630 --> 00:28:39,110
and working towards agreement there,

671
00:28:39,110 --> 00:28:40,390
and again, it will always,

672
00:28:40,390 --> 00:28:41,630
and then we've got an email track

673
00:28:41,630 --> 00:28:43,550
and I'll always summarize in the emails

674
00:28:43,550 --> 00:28:45,510
as we're sort of building up towards agreement.

675
00:28:45,510 --> 00:28:46,390
But at the end of the day,

676
00:28:46,390 --> 00:28:47,790
when we have reached agreement,

677
00:28:47,790 --> 00:28:49,230
you know, I will always make sure

678
00:28:49,230 --> 00:28:50,350
to have something signed.

679
00:28:50,350 --> 00:28:52,030
Now, one mistake that I've made in the past,

680
00:28:52,030 --> 00:28:53,510
and I don't make it anymore,

681
00:28:53,510 --> 00:28:55,470
is that what has happened in the past

682
00:28:55,470 --> 00:28:56,310
is the attorneys say,

683
00:28:56,310 --> 00:28:57,150
well, yes, thank you,

684
00:28:57,150 --> 00:28:58,150
I think we've got it from here,

685
00:28:58,150 --> 00:28:59,670
and I think they've got it from there.

686
00:28:59,670 --> 00:29:00,510
But they haven't.

687
00:29:00,510 --> 00:29:01,470
It falls apart.

688
00:29:01,470 --> 00:29:03,790
So I never leave it to the attorneys

689
00:29:03,790 --> 00:29:05,390
until we've got something signed.

690
00:29:05,390 --> 00:29:06,790
So when they say to me,

691
00:29:06,790 --> 00:29:08,270
yes, you know, we think we've got it from here,

692
00:29:08,270 --> 00:29:09,390
no, they haven't got it from there.

693
00:29:09,390 --> 00:29:10,350
They make a mess of it,

694
00:29:10,350 --> 00:29:11,430
nine times out of 10.

695
00:29:11,430 --> 00:29:12,950
So I need to stay involved

696
00:29:12,950 --> 00:29:14,350
until we've got something signed.

697
00:29:14,350 --> 00:29:15,470
You ever had a situation

698
00:29:15,470 --> 00:29:18,590
where someone has used the mediation process

699
00:29:18,590 --> 00:29:20,990
to escalate the situation

700
00:29:20,990 --> 00:29:23,990
and purposefully evade solution

701
00:29:23,990 --> 00:29:26,150
to try and drive it towards

702
00:29:26,150 --> 00:29:28,030
more of the right-hand side of the spectrum

703
00:29:28,030 --> 00:29:29,950
to get to litigation?

704
00:29:29,950 --> 00:29:30,910
The only time that happens

705
00:29:30,910 --> 00:29:32,190
is in coded mediation.

706
00:29:32,190 --> 00:29:34,230
So, for example, in many districts,

707
00:29:34,230 --> 00:29:35,550
and I'm sure it's in Canada as well,

708
00:29:35,550 --> 00:29:37,030
particularly in family law,

709
00:29:37,030 --> 00:29:38,310
probably more common in family law

710
00:29:38,310 --> 00:29:39,190
than anything else,

711
00:29:39,190 --> 00:29:41,230
is where the judge will order mediation.

712
00:29:41,230 --> 00:29:42,070
And not only that,

713
00:29:42,070 --> 00:29:45,510
it's oftentimes ordered within the court system

714
00:29:45,510 --> 00:29:46,990
whereby they've got mediators

715
00:29:46,990 --> 00:29:49,110
that are not terribly well trained or qualified,

716
00:29:49,110 --> 00:29:50,310
and they'll spend two or three hours

717
00:29:50,310 --> 00:29:52,230
with the parties to try to mediate a solution.

718
00:29:52,230 --> 00:29:53,070
But even if it's not,

719
00:29:53,070 --> 00:29:54,790
if they come because the judge has ordered it,

720
00:29:54,790 --> 00:29:55,750
sometimes it's a danger

721
00:29:55,750 --> 00:29:59,030
that a pro forma to move beyond to litigation.

722
00:29:59,030 --> 00:30:00,470
So you've got to be a little careful of that.

723
00:30:00,470 --> 00:30:01,270
And if that is the case,

724
00:30:01,270 --> 00:30:02,830
if it's a court ordered mediation,

725
00:30:02,830 --> 00:30:04,150
you suspect that's what it is,

726
00:30:04,150 --> 00:30:05,710
you're better off spending time

727
00:30:05,710 --> 00:30:06,550
in that mediation,

728
00:30:06,550 --> 00:30:07,990
educating the parties

729
00:30:07,990 --> 00:30:09,070
about what it looks like

730
00:30:09,070 --> 00:30:09,990
moving towards the right

731
00:30:09,990 --> 00:30:12,670
and what the options are of resolution

732
00:30:12,670 --> 00:30:13,870
rather than trying to go straight

733
00:30:13,870 --> 00:30:15,310
into the mediation process.

734
00:30:15,310 --> 00:30:17,310
I'm going to paint a picture for you

735
00:30:17,310 --> 00:30:18,790
and I'd like to see how you would respond.

736
00:30:18,790 --> 00:30:20,830
Now, this is a specific example,

737
00:30:20,830 --> 00:30:22,150
and you could tell me

738
00:30:22,150 --> 00:30:23,670
that this doesn't necessarily make sense

739
00:30:23,670 --> 00:30:24,910
if it doesn't make sense for you.

740
00:30:24,910 --> 00:30:26,030
Let's say, for example,

741
00:30:26,030 --> 00:30:27,030
you get to a point

742
00:30:27,030 --> 00:30:28,790
where the only option

743
00:30:28,790 --> 00:30:30,710
is to go to litigation.

744
00:30:30,710 --> 00:30:31,830
Both parties are fighting.

745
00:30:31,830 --> 00:30:33,270
You can't find a way for people

746
00:30:33,270 --> 00:30:34,630
to agree with each other.

747
00:30:34,630 --> 00:30:37,590
You've gone from negotiation to mediation,

748
00:30:37,590 --> 00:30:39,550
maybe even explored arbitration,

749
00:30:39,550 --> 00:30:40,470
but they've just decided,

750
00:30:40,470 --> 00:30:42,990
screw it, we're going to go straight to litigation.

751
00:30:42,990 --> 00:30:44,670
Do you have like a Hail Mary

752
00:30:44,670 --> 00:30:45,870
that you throw at the end

753
00:30:45,870 --> 00:30:47,870
to try and stop that from happening?

754
00:30:47,870 --> 00:30:49,230
Or do you just say,

755
00:30:49,230 --> 00:30:50,950
all right, I've done what I have to do.

756
00:30:50,950 --> 00:30:51,790
And you know,

757
00:30:51,790 --> 00:30:53,470
what's the way that you sleep well at night

758
00:30:53,470 --> 00:30:54,870
knowing that you've done

759
00:30:54,870 --> 00:30:55,950
everything that you can do

760
00:30:55,950 --> 00:30:58,550
before they try and destroy each other in court?

761
00:30:58,550 --> 00:30:59,910
Well, two responses to that.

762
00:30:59,910 --> 00:31:00,790
The first response is that

763
00:31:00,790 --> 00:31:02,030
in order to resolve a dispute,

764
00:31:02,030 --> 00:31:03,710
it has to be ripe for resolution,

765
00:31:03,710 --> 00:31:04,390
as I call it.

766
00:31:04,390 --> 00:31:06,190
And sometimes it's not ripe for resolution.

767
00:31:06,190 --> 00:31:08,350
It's again, like international affairs,

768
00:31:08,350 --> 00:31:09,190
where sometimes there have to be

769
00:31:09,190 --> 00:31:11,030
a few shots fired across the border

770
00:31:11,030 --> 00:31:12,630
until both parties realize

771
00:31:12,630 --> 00:31:13,870
what we're getting ourselves into.

772
00:31:13,870 --> 00:31:14,750
That's the one aspect.

773
00:31:14,750 --> 00:31:15,630
You've got to ask yourself,

774
00:31:15,630 --> 00:31:17,910
is this dispute actually ripe for resolution?

775
00:31:17,910 --> 00:31:19,030
And it may not be.

776
00:31:19,030 --> 00:31:20,030
They may have to go through

777
00:31:20,030 --> 00:31:22,430
some volleys of litigation

778
00:31:22,430 --> 00:31:24,390
before it actually becomes ripe for resolution.

779
00:31:24,390 --> 00:31:25,510
The second point I want to make

780
00:31:25,510 --> 00:31:26,430
is when a person says,

781
00:31:26,430 --> 00:31:27,950
I want to litigate this,

782
00:31:27,950 --> 00:31:31,630
in using our negotiation jargon, if you will,

783
00:31:31,630 --> 00:31:33,110
essentially that's a position.

784
00:31:33,110 --> 00:31:34,310
That's again, a rigid position.

785
00:31:34,310 --> 00:31:35,470
I'm going to litigate.

786
00:31:35,470 --> 00:31:36,910
And we can treat that as a position

787
00:31:36,910 --> 00:31:38,550
and try to find the interests.

788
00:31:38,550 --> 00:31:40,030
Why would you litigate?

789
00:31:40,030 --> 00:31:41,510
For what purpose would you litigate?

790
00:31:41,510 --> 00:31:44,230
And what would be your underlying interest

791
00:31:44,230 --> 00:31:47,070
in litigating as opposed to finding some

792
00:31:47,070 --> 00:31:49,190
cheaper and more effective means of resolution?

793
00:31:49,190 --> 00:31:50,910
And sort of walking them down that path

794
00:31:50,910 --> 00:31:52,470
of trying to understand what those interests

795
00:31:52,470 --> 00:31:53,790
and trying to loosen, again,

796
00:31:53,790 --> 00:31:55,790
those deep roots of that big oak tree.

797
00:31:55,790 --> 00:31:56,630
Yeah.

798
00:31:56,630 --> 00:31:57,830
But again, never imposing, never say,

799
00:31:58,190 --> 00:31:59,190
if they decide that's what it is,

800
00:31:59,190 --> 00:32:00,830
you've got to be able to walk away.

801
00:32:00,830 --> 00:32:03,430
Try to help them to sort of see what that looks like

802
00:32:03,430 --> 00:32:05,030
and try to understand what some of the interests are,

803
00:32:05,030 --> 00:32:06,510
try to find other solutions.

804
00:32:06,510 --> 00:32:07,350
And you might say,

805
00:32:07,350 --> 00:32:08,710
well, I'm just afraid that I'll agree

806
00:32:08,710 --> 00:32:09,910
to something I might regret.

807
00:32:09,910 --> 00:32:11,150
So at that point I'll say,

808
00:32:11,150 --> 00:32:12,550
but how about we try to mediate

809
00:32:12,550 --> 00:32:13,790
and look at some various options

810
00:32:13,790 --> 00:32:14,910
without any commitment?

811
00:32:14,910 --> 00:32:17,750
Then I'll try to find solutions to the interests

812
00:32:17,750 --> 00:32:20,030
as opposed to responding to the position.

813
00:32:20,030 --> 00:32:21,550
This is my interpretation.

814
00:32:21,550 --> 00:32:23,270
I find the mediation process to be

815
00:32:23,270 --> 00:32:25,870
a lot more collaborative than the litigation process,

816
00:32:25,870 --> 00:32:27,550
at least on the surface from an outsider

817
00:32:28,150 --> 00:32:30,350
I was chatting with a litigator once

818
00:32:30,350 --> 00:32:32,230
who was the chief litigator of a firm,

819
00:32:32,230 --> 00:32:33,270
which I won't name,

820
00:32:33,270 --> 00:32:36,910
but that person was seen as like the chief attack dog

821
00:32:36,910 --> 00:32:38,350
of that organization.

822
00:32:38,350 --> 00:32:40,990
And their job was solely to seek and destroy

823
00:32:40,990 --> 00:32:42,950
and like go in and destroy

824
00:32:42,950 --> 00:32:45,430
as much as humanly possible of the other party.

825
00:32:45,430 --> 00:32:46,750
It wasn't collaborative.

826
00:32:46,750 --> 00:32:50,110
There was no sort of way to find common interests.

827
00:32:50,110 --> 00:32:52,150
It was attack, attack all the time.

828
00:32:52,150 --> 00:32:54,310
And that person was built for that role, right?

829
00:32:54,310 --> 00:32:55,710
And there are certain litigators

830
00:32:55,710 --> 00:32:58,110
that are just designed purely for that role.

831
00:32:58,110 --> 00:32:59,350
And we need those people.

832
00:32:59,350 --> 00:33:01,030
I'm not saying that we don't need those people,

833
00:33:01,030 --> 00:33:05,030
but it seemed like such a acidic process

834
00:33:05,030 --> 00:33:07,270
and such a vindictive process

835
00:33:07,270 --> 00:33:08,710
that on the surface it was just like,

836
00:33:08,710 --> 00:33:09,830
whoa, this is crazy.

837
00:33:09,830 --> 00:33:12,190
This guy, all he thought about was attack.

838
00:33:12,190 --> 00:33:14,230
It didn't seem collaborative whatsoever.

839
00:33:14,230 --> 00:33:15,070
Am I wrong there?

840
00:33:15,070 --> 00:33:16,230
No, you're absolutely right.

841
00:33:16,230 --> 00:33:17,470
And as you mentioned correctly,

842
00:33:17,470 --> 00:33:18,630
sometimes we need that.

843
00:33:18,630 --> 00:33:20,310
The problem is in corporations

844
00:33:20,310 --> 00:33:21,790
where they have in-house counsel,

845
00:33:21,790 --> 00:33:22,950
that's all they have.

846
00:33:22,950 --> 00:33:24,110
And the way I look at it is

847
00:33:24,110 --> 00:33:26,150
you need both the Department of Defense,

848
00:33:26,150 --> 00:33:27,390
which is what that is,

849
00:33:27,390 --> 00:33:29,470
and you need a Department of State,

850
00:33:29,470 --> 00:33:30,910
which deals with the diplomacy side

851
00:33:30,910 --> 00:33:32,350
and they need to balance one another out.

852
00:33:32,350 --> 00:33:33,830
The problem is in many situations,

853
00:33:33,830 --> 00:33:34,790
such as that corporation

854
00:33:34,790 --> 00:33:36,270
and many corporations like that

855
00:33:36,270 --> 00:33:37,750
have the Department of Defense,

856
00:33:37,750 --> 00:33:39,230
but they don't have the Department of State.

857
00:33:39,230 --> 00:33:41,310
And I think corporation would be well served

858
00:33:41,310 --> 00:33:43,350
to have both those departments,

859
00:33:43,350 --> 00:33:44,710
in-house legal teams,

860
00:33:44,710 --> 00:33:45,790
both the Department of Defense

861
00:33:45,790 --> 00:33:47,190
and the Department of State

862
00:33:47,190 --> 00:33:48,710
and use them as necessary.

863
00:33:48,710 --> 00:33:50,310
Imagine the United States,

864
00:33:50,310 --> 00:33:52,270
well, it's hard to imagine the United States anyway.

865
00:33:52,270 --> 00:33:53,190
Imagine the United States

866
00:33:53,190 --> 00:33:55,590
to the Department of Defense only

867
00:33:55,590 --> 00:33:56,670
and no Department of State.

868
00:33:56,670 --> 00:33:58,190
Yeah, and no diplomacy.

869
00:33:58,190 --> 00:33:59,150
Yes.

870
00:33:59,150 --> 00:33:59,990
Yeah, interesting.

871
00:33:59,990 --> 00:34:02,150
I like the way that you tie that to,

872
00:34:02,150 --> 00:34:04,630
essentially it would be like a large organization

873
00:34:04,630 --> 00:34:06,190
is much like a government,

874
00:34:06,190 --> 00:34:07,190
to a large extent.

875
00:34:07,190 --> 00:34:08,030
It is.

876
00:34:08,030 --> 00:34:09,190
And having those departments are key,

877
00:34:09,190 --> 00:34:10,830
whether or not they're individual people

878
00:34:10,830 --> 00:34:12,070
is another thing in town.

879
00:34:12,070 --> 00:34:13,030
Right, right, right.

880
00:34:13,030 --> 00:34:15,750
In fact, a large corporation being well advised

881
00:34:15,750 --> 00:34:18,110
to actually have a completely separate Department of State

882
00:34:18,110 --> 00:34:19,710
with a VP of negotiation

883
00:34:19,710 --> 00:34:21,670
and dispute resolution and so on.

884
00:34:21,670 --> 00:34:23,990
I've seen a lot of chatter about this recently

885
00:34:23,990 --> 00:34:26,510
where people are arguing for sort of like

886
00:34:26,510 --> 00:34:29,230
the chief negotiation officer role

887
00:34:29,230 --> 00:34:32,030
within an organization to keep that diplomacy going.

888
00:34:32,030 --> 00:34:32,870
Correct.

889
00:34:32,870 --> 00:34:34,710
I think that's something we may be worth looking at

890
00:34:34,710 --> 00:34:36,030
for larger corporations.

891
